---
/*
  /sdk — the SDK and CLI reference.

  Comprehensive reference for the vela CLI, the Rust crates, and the
  Python and TypeScript reducer bindings. Designed so a researcher or
  research engineer can integrate without contacting the team.
*/

import Reading from "../layouts/Reading.astro";
import { REPO_URL, HUB_URL } from "../config";
---

<Reading
  title="SDK reference · Vela"
  description="CLI, Rust crates, Python and TypeScript reducer bindings, hub HTTP API. Reference for integrating with the substrate."
  active="docs"
>
  <header class="page-head">
    <p class="eyebrow">Vela · SDK reference</p>
    <h1 class="page-head__title">Build against the substrate.</h1>
    <p class="page-head__sub">
      The CLI, the Rust crates, the Python and TypeScript reducer bindings, and the hub
      HTTP API. Everything a researcher or research engineer needs to integrate without
      contacting the team.
    </p>
  </header>

  <article class="sdk">

    <nav class="sdk__toc" aria-label="On this page">
      <p class="sdk__toc-eyebrow">On this page</p>
      <ol class="sdk__toc-list">
        <li><a href="#cli">§1 · vela CLI</a></li>
        <li><a href="#rust">§2 · Rust crates</a></li>
        <li><a href="#python">§3 · Python reducer</a></li>
        <li><a href="#typescript">§4 · TypeScript reducer</a></li>
        <li><a href="#http">§5 · Hub HTTP API</a></li>
        <li><a href="#schema">§6 · Event schema</a></li>
      </ol>
    </nav>

    <!-- ── CLI ── -->
    <section class="sdk__section" id="cli">
      <header class="sdk__head">
        <span class="sdk__num">§1</span>
        <h2 class="sdk__title">vela CLI</h2>
      </header>

      <p class="sdk__intro">
        The <code>vela</code> binary is the canonical write surface. Every command produces a
        signed event that any reducer in the world can replay byte-for-byte. New users should
        start with <a class="inline-link" href="/quickstart">/quickstart</a> for the end-to-end
        loop; this section is the reference.
      </p>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>vela frontier new</code></h3>
        <p>Scaffold a publishable <code>frontier.json</code>.</p>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>vela frontier new --name &lt;NAME&gt; [--description &lt;TEXT&gt;] [--force] &lt;PATH&gt;</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>vela init</code></h3>
        <p>Initialize a local <code>.vela/</code> repo (not directly publishable; use <code>frontier new</code> for hub-bound work).</p>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>vela init [--name &lt;NAME&gt;] [&lt;PATH&gt;]</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>vela finding add</code></h3>
        <p>Add a finding to a frontier. Without <code>--apply</code> it lands as a pending proposal in the inbox.</p>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>vela finding add &lt;FRONTIER&gt; \
    --assertion &lt;TEXT&gt; \
    --author &lt;ACTOR-ID&gt; \
    [--type mechanism|therapeutic|diagnostic|epidemiological|...] \
    [--source &lt;LABEL&gt;] [--source-type published_paper|preprint|...] \
    [--confidence 0.0-1.0] \
    [--evidence-type experimental|observational|...] \
    [--entities name:type,name:type,...] \
    [--doi &lt;DOI&gt;] [--pmid &lt;PMID&gt;] [--year &lt;YYYY&gt;] \
    [--apply]</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>vela finding supersede</code></h3>
        <p>Supersede an existing finding with a revised content-addressed claim. Old finding flagged <code>superseded</code>; new finding gets an auto-injected <code>supersedes</code> link.</p>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>vela finding supersede &lt;FRONTIER&gt; \
    --supersedes &lt;FINDING-ID&gt; \
    --assertion &lt;TEXT&gt; \
    --author &lt;ACTOR-ID&gt; \
    [--confidence 0.0-1.0] \
    [--apply]</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>vela link add</code></h3>
        <p>Typed edge between two findings. Cross-frontier targets use <code>vf_…@vfr_…</code> form.</p>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>vela link add &lt;FRONTIER&gt; \
    --from &lt;FINDING-ID&gt; \
    --to &lt;FINDING-ID&gt; \
    --type supports|depends|contradicts|narrows|supersedes</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>vela sign</code></h3>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>vela sign generate-keypair [--out &lt;DIR&gt;]
vela sign apply &lt;FRONTIER&gt; --private-key &lt;PATH&gt;
vela sign verify &lt;FRONTIER&gt; [--public-key &lt;PATH&gt;]
vela sign threshold-set &lt;FRONTIER&gt; &lt;FINDING-ID&gt; --to &lt;N&gt;</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>vela actor add</code></h3>
        <p>Register an Ed25519 public key for a stable actor identity.</p>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>vela actor add &lt;FRONTIER&gt; &lt;ACTOR-ID&gt; --pubkey &lt;HEX&gt; [--orcid &lt;ORCID&gt;]
vela actor list &lt;FRONTIER&gt;</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>vela registry</code></h3>
        <p>Publish, list, pull, and mirror frontier manifests.</p>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>vela registry publish &lt;FRONTIER&gt; \
    --owner &lt;ACTOR-ID&gt; --key &lt;PRIVATE-KEY&gt; \
    --locator &lt;URL&gt; [--to &lt;HUB&gt;]

vela registry list [--from &lt;HUB&gt;]
vela registry pull &lt;VFR-ID&gt; [--from &lt;HUB&gt;] [--to &lt;PATH&gt;]
vela registry mirror --vfr-id &lt;VFR-ID&gt; --from &lt;HUB&gt; --to &lt;HUB&gt;</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>vela workbench</code></h3>
        <p>Launch the local workbench web app against a Vela repo.</p>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>vela workbench [&lt;PATH&gt;] [--port &lt;PORT&gt;] [--no-open]</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name">Agent commands (Vela's bundled agents)</h3>
        <p>LLM-backed pipelines that walk source material and write <code>finding.add</code> proposals tagged with an <code>AgentRun</code> record (full schema in <a class="inline-link" href="/spec#agent-run">/spec § 4 · AgentRun</a>). Reviewers accept via the inbox; nothing becomes canonical without a separate signed <code>finding-accepted</code> from a registered reviewer.</p>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>vela scout         &lt;FOLDER&gt; --frontier &lt;PATH&gt;   # Literature Scout (PDFs)
vela compile-notes &lt;VAULT&gt;  --frontier &lt;PATH&gt;   # Markdown / Obsidian
vela compile-code  &lt;ROOT&gt;   --frontier &lt;PATH&gt;   # Jupyter / Python / R
vela compile-data  &lt;ROOT&gt;   --frontier &lt;PATH&gt;   # CSV / Parquet
vela review-pending      --frontier &lt;PATH&gt;   # Reviewer Agent
vela find-tensions       --frontier &lt;PATH&gt;   # Contradiction Finder
vela plan-experiments    --frontier &lt;PATH&gt;   # Experiment Planner</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name">Agent SDK — third-party integration</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Status:</strong> Spec'd, not yet shipped. The CLI agents above are
          Vela's bundled pipelines — useful as reference implementations but not how an
          AI lab integrates its own agents. The third-party agent SDK lives in two
          packages, on the roadmap for v0.50:
        </p>
        <ul class="sdk__flags">
          <li><code>vela-py</code> (Python) — <code>vela.publish_proposal(event,
            agent_run=…)</code> signs a <code>finding-drafted</code> in-process and POSTs
            to a hub. Idempotency tokens, batch publish, streaming inbox subscription.</li>
          <li><code>vela-ts</code> (TypeScript) — same surface, ESM module for
            Node and edge runtimes; same wire-format guarantees as the existing
            <code>vela_reducer.mjs</code>.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Until the SDK ships, third-party integrators drive Vela through the CLI by
          shelling out to the binary. That works but it isn't how production agent
          orchestrators want to operate. The hub already implements the agent-traffic
          semantics (<a class="inline-link" href="/spec#hub-agent-traffic">/spec § 7 · agent
          traffic</a>: idempotency keys, batch publish, streaming inbox); the SDK is the
          missing language binding, not a missing protocol surface.
        </p>
        <p>
          A reference Python wrapper that signs <code>finding-drafted</code> events with
          your own Ed25519 key (~80 lines, stdlib + <code>cryptography</code>) is in
          <code>tools/agent-sdk-skeleton.py</code> on the repo. It is not tagged
          conformant; it is a starting point for an external implementer.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name">Causal reasoning</h3>
        <p>Pearl-tier queries against the link graph.</p>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>vela causal audit       &lt;FRONTIER&gt;                     # per-finding identifiability
vela causal effect      &lt;FRONTIER&gt; &lt;SOURCE&gt; --on &lt;TGT&gt;  # back-door / front-door (Pearl L2)
vela causal counterfactual &lt;FRONTIER&gt; &lt;SRC&gt; --target &lt;TGT&gt; --set-to &lt;0..1&gt;  # twin-network (L3)
vela causal graph       &lt;FRONTIER&gt;                     # print the directed link graph</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name">Cross-frontier composition</h3>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>vela frontier add-dep    &lt;FRONTIER&gt; --vfr-id &lt;ID&gt; --snapshot &lt;HASH&gt;
vela frontier refresh-deps &lt;FRONTIER&gt;                  # re-pin to current hub snapshots
vela bridges derive      &lt;A.json&gt; &lt;B.json&gt;              # cross-frontier hypotheses
vela bridges confirm     &lt;FRONTIER&gt; &lt;BRIDGE-ID&gt; --reviewer &lt;ID&gt;</code></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Rust ── -->
    <section class="sdk__section" id="rust">
      <header class="sdk__head">
        <span class="sdk__num">§2</span>
        <h2 class="sdk__title">Rust crates</h2>
      </header>

      <p class="sdk__intro">
        The canonical reducer is implemented in Rust. Three crates compose the workspace.
      </p>

      <dl class="sdk__pair">
        <dt><code>vela-protocol</code></dt>
        <dd>The protocol types: <code>Event</code>, <code>Finding</code>,
          <code>EvidenceObject</code>, <code>Correction</code>, <code>Signature</code>,
          canonical-JSON serialization, hash-of-canonical signing surface. Pure
          <code>no_std</code>-compatible types with serde.</dd>
        <dt><code>vela-reducer</code></dt>
        <dd>The deterministic state machine. <code>fn reduce(events: &amp;[Event]) -&gt;
          Frontier</code>. Byte-identical output across machines and versions for any given
          event log. Test fixtures verify byte-equality with the Python and TypeScript
          reducers.</dd>
        <dt><code>vela-hub</code></dt>
        <dd>The HTTP server (axum) that accepts signed events, persists the log, and serves
          the canonical state. The <code>vela-hub</code> binary is what runs at
          <a class="inline-link" href={HUB_URL} rel="noopener">{HUB_URL.replace(/^https?:\/\//, '')}</a>.</dd>
      </dl>

      <p>Add the crates to a Rust project from the workspace root.</p>
      <pre class="sdk__code"><code>[dependencies]
vela-protocol = {`{ git = "${REPO_URL}", branch = "main" }`}
vela-reducer  = {`{ git = "${REPO_URL}", branch = "main" }`}</code></pre>

      <p>Replay an event log from disk:</p>
      <pre class="sdk__code"><code>use vela_protocol::Event;
use vela_reducer::reduce;

let events: Vec&lt;Event&gt; = std::fs::read_dir(".vela/events")?
    .map(|e| serde_json::from_slice(&amp;std::fs::read(e?.path())?))
    .collect::&lt;Result&lt;_, _&gt;&gt;()?;

let frontier = reduce(&amp;events);
println!("findings: {`{}`}", frontier.findings.len());</code></pre>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Python ── -->
    <section class="sdk__section" id="python">
      <header class="sdk__head">
        <span class="sdk__num">§3</span>
        <h2 class="sdk__title">Python reducer</h2>
      </header>

      <p class="sdk__intro">
        Stdlib-only verifier and reducer. Designed to be auditable in one sitting and
        installable with no transitive dependencies — the same constraint that lets the
        thirty-second proof at <a class="inline-link" href="/try">/try</a> run on any laptop.
      </p>

      <pre class="sdk__code"><code>from vela_reducer import reduce, verify_signature

with open(".vela/events/0001-finding-drafted.json") as f:
    events = [json.loads(line) for line in f]

frontier = reduce(events)
assert verify_signature(events[0])
print(f"findings: {`{len(frontier['findings'])}`}")</code></pre>

      <p>
        Source at <a class="inline-link" href="/vela_reducer.py">vela_reducer.py</a> on this
        domain. Stdlib-only. Auditable end-to-end in roughly 600 lines.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- ── TypeScript ── -->
    <section class="sdk__section" id="typescript">
      <header class="sdk__head">
        <span class="sdk__num">§4</span>
        <h2 class="sdk__title">TypeScript reducer</h2>
      </header>

      <p class="sdk__intro">
        ESM module, runs in node and modern browsers without polyfills. Used by the workbench
        to replay state in the client and verify signatures locally.
      </p>

      <pre class="sdk__code"><code>import {`{ reduce, verifySignature }`} from "/vela_reducer.mjs";

const events = await fetch("/api/frontier/vfr_bd91/events")
    .then(r =&gt; r.json());

const frontier = reduce(events);
const allValid = events.every(verifySignature);
console.log(`findings: ${`{frontier.findings.length}`}, valid: ${`{allValid}`}`);</code></pre>

      <p>Source at <a class="inline-link" href="/vela_reducer.mjs">vela_reducer.mjs</a>. ESM module, no build step required.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- ── HTTP API ── -->
    <section class="sdk__section" id="http">
      <header class="sdk__head">
        <span class="sdk__num">§5</span>
        <h2 class="sdk__title">Hub HTTP API</h2>
      </header>

      <p class="sdk__intro">
        The canonical hub at <a class="inline-link" href={HUB_URL} rel="noopener">{HUB_URL.replace(/^https?:\/\//, '')}</a>.
        No authentication, no rate limiting, CORS open. The signature scheme is the bind.
      </p>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>GET /entries</code></h3>
        <p>List all known frontier entries.</p>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>curl {HUB_URL}/entries</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>GET /entries/{`{vfr_id}`}</code></h3>
        <p>Get a single frontier's signed manifest and event count.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>GET /frontier/{`{vfr_id}`}/events</code></h3>
        <p>Stream the full event log for a frontier as newline-delimited JSON.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>GET /frontier/{`{vfr_id}`}/snapshot</code></h3>
        <p>Server-computed reduced state. Byte-identical to what your local reducer produces.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>POST /publish</code></h3>
        <p>Append a signed event log to a frontier. Body is newline-delimited signed events.</p>
        <pre class="sdk__code"><code>curl -X POST {HUB_URL}/publish \
    -H "content-type: application/jsonl" \
    --data-binary @.vela/events/0001-finding-drafted.json</code></pre>
        <p>The hub validates each signature; events with invalid signatures are rejected with HTTP 400.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sdk__cmd">
        <h3 class="sdk__cmd-name"><code>GET /.well-known/vela</code></h3>
        <p>Discovery endpoint. Returns hub capabilities, supported protocol versions, signing
          algorithm (always <code>ed25519-canonical-json-v1</code>), and admin contact.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Schema ── -->
    <section class="sdk__section" id="schema">
      <header class="sdk__head">
        <span class="sdk__num">§6</span>
        <h2 class="sdk__title">Event schema</h2>
      </header>

      <p class="sdk__intro">
        Every event is canonical-JSON, signed with Ed25519 over the byte-canonical
        serialization (no pre-hash). The four primitive event types share a common envelope.
      </p>

      <pre class="sdk__code"><code>{`{
  "v": 1,                              // protocol version
  "id": "ev_8a3e...",                  // content-addressed event id
  "ts": "2026-05-02T15:42:01Z",        // ISO-8601 UTC, monotonic per actor
  "actor": "did:key:z6Mk...",          // signer's verifying key
  "kind": "finding-drafted",           // event type
  "frontier": "vfr_bd91...",           // target frontier
  "payload": { ... },                  // type-specific body
  "sig": "ed25519:8c2a9f..."           // signature over canonical bytes
}`}</code></pre>

      <p>Full schema documentation, including the payload shape for each event kind, lives in
        the protocol spec at <a class="inline-link" href="/spec">/spec</a>. The
        <a class="inline-link" href="/primitives/">primitives appendix</a> walks the
        information model in prose.</p>
    </section>

  </article>
</Reading>

